<Author>bscuga
<Content>Great Stay I stayed at the Ritz-Carlton on Financial Street in Beijing, China on June 3, 2007 - June 9, 2007. The hotel itself was wonderful. I would be remiss if I did not advise everyone that I have never stayed at a Ritz before, so I don't can't compare this hotel to other Ritz-Carlton's. Everyone in the hotel, with the exception of some of the massage specialists, spoke English very well. The hotel allowed money to be exchanged at a rate that is controlled by the Chinese government. Be careful when bringing bills that are bent or worn because it might not be allowed to be exchanged because of the Bank that the Ritz gives the money to. The breakfast were both western and eastern, so there was something for everyone. Be careful when requesting bottled water at breakfast (or any other time) because it is 55 RMB about $7.25. Each day, your room receives two bottles of Chinese water (remember, the Ritz is not in the habit of making there guests sick, so the water is safe and there is not aftertaste) and the spa/workout area has free bottles available at anytime. If you are price sensitive, there is a gas station a couple of blocks down the street that sells cheap Coca-Colas (no Diet Coke or Coca-Cola Lite) that is within walking distance. The same restuarant that serves breakfast also serves lunch and dinner and the prices can be more expensive than what you would get outside the hotel. There is another restuarant which is near the mall entrance (the mall was not open when I was there) that serves upscale Italian (if I recall correctly) and the meal (lobster with pasta) I had there was the best meal I had in two weeks in China. I would like to say that I was not a big fan of the Chinese Chinese food as opposed to the American Chinese food and craved Western food. Outside of the hotel there are several Western restuarants (Pizza Hut, Friday's, KFC) if you are craving something from home.Since the hotel is fairly new, a lot of the taxi drivers do not know where it is located. I never saw Chinese text for Financial Street. The employees are happy to translate for you on the way out, but make sure you bring a business card or map that the Ritz can provide with directions and the location of the hotel. If you go to the Forbidden City from the hotel, you should not pay more than 25 RMB.I had two massages while I stayed at the Ritz and they were both wonderful. The massages are the equivilant of what you would find in the States in terms of prices. The workout room has TVs all over the place. The pool is nothing to write home about and I could not find a jacuzzi.The one downside of the hotel is that there is not much near the hotel so you will need to get a taxi. Taxis are extremely cheap (at the current exchange rate of 7.60:1).I stayed in a regular room with two full size beds. Each room had a desk with internet connection (you have to pay for it) and a nice bathroom. There is free internet connection in the lobby and we found out that you can get the connection in the lobby and bring it to you room (without plugging in) for about 24 hours before needing to go get the connection. If you bring your laptop, make sure you download Skype (or a program like it) for 2.1 cents per minute to the USA. You just speak on your computer's mic (built in or bought) and call a landline or cell phone. 
